<BaseLayout
  title="Why gambling is everywhere now"
  description="A 2018 Supreme Court decision, gambling on phones, and newer money activities that share features with gambling — the plain-language explanation of why this all feels so recent."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="page-header__eyebrow">
        <a href="/understand-gambling">← Understand gambling</a>
      </p>
      <h1>Why gambling is everywhere now</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        If it feels like gambling is suddenly everywhere — on TV during
        games, in app stores, in ads on your phone — you are not
        imagining it. Here's the plain-language version of what
        changed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>The short version</h2>
      <p>
        A few things changed at once. A 2018 U.S. Supreme Court decision
        let each state decide whether to allow legal sports betting,
        and many states did. Gambling also moved online, so a casino or
        a lottery can now live on your phone. And some newer money
        activities, like trading crypto or certain kinds of
        investments, can look and feel a lot like gambling.
      </p>
      <p>
        This page explains what changed, in plain terms. It does not
        tell you whether to gamble, invest, or trade. It is just here
        to help you understand the landscape.
      </p>

      <h2>The legal turning point: PASPA and Murphy v. NCAA</h2>
      <p>
        For about 25 years, a federal law mostly kept legal sports
        betting out of most of the country.
      </p>
      <p>
        That law was the <strong>Professional and Amateur Sports
        Protection Act</strong>, usually shortened to <strong>PASPA</strong>.
        Congress passed it in <strong>1992</strong>. In simple terms,
        PASPA blocked states from authorizing sports betting. Nevada,
        which already had legal sports betting, was largely the
        exception (SCOTUSblog, 2018).
      </p>
      <p>
        Then, on <strong>May 14, 2018</strong>, the U.S. Supreme Court
        struck PASPA down in a case called <strong>Murphy v. National
        Collegiate Athletic Association (Murphy v. NCAA)</strong>. The
        vote was 6–3, and Justice Samuel Alito wrote the main opinion.
        The Court found that PASPA broke a constitutional rule (called
        the "anticommandeering" rule) about what the federal government
        can order states to do (SCOTUSblog, 2018; Oyez, 2018).
      </p>
      <p>
        Here is the plain-language version of what that meant: striking
        down PASPA did not make sports betting legal everywhere by
        itself. Instead, it handed the decision back to <strong>each
        state</strong>. After that, states were free to choose for
        themselves.
      </p>
      <p>
        Many of them did. Since 2018, legal sports betting has spread
        state by state. As of 2025, about <strong>39 states plus
        Washington, D.C.,</strong> allowed sports betting in some form,
        and most of those offered it online or on mobile phones (Legal
        Sports Report, 2025; PGA Tour, 2024). Because new states keep
        being added, that number is a snapshot in time, not a fixed
        total.
      </p>
      <p>
        So when people ask, "Why is sports betting suddenly on every
        screen?" — the 2018 <em>Murphy</em> decision is a big part of
        the answer.
      </p>

      <h2>Going online: iGaming and iLottery</h2>
      <p>
        The other big change is <em>where</em> gambling happens. It
        used to mean going somewhere — a casino, a track, a store
        counter. More and more, it can happen on a phone or computer.
      </p>
      <p>Two terms come up a lot:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>iGaming</strong> usually means <strong>online casino
          games</strong> — things like online slots, blackjack,
          roulette, and poker, played over the internet instead of in
          a building. As of 2025, a small group of states had legalized
          online casino play, including New Jersey, Pennsylvania,
          Michigan, and a few others (CBS Sports, 2025; American
          Gaming Association, 2025).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>iLottery</strong> means buying <strong>lottery
          tickets or playing lottery games online</strong>, through a
          website or app, instead of at a store. A growing number of
          states offer some form of online lottery, and more have been
          moving in that direction (WilmerHale, 2025).
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>Why does moving online matter for understanding gambling? A few plain reasons:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>More access.</strong> A phone is always nearby. There
          is no closing time and no drive home.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>More often.</strong> When something is one tap away,
          it is easier to do it many times a day.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Fewer natural stopping points.</strong> In a physical
          casino or store, there are pauses — leaving, standing in
          line, running out of cash on hand. Online, those built-in
          pauses can disappear.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        None of this means online gambling is "bad." It simply means
        access has grown, and for some people more access can make it
        harder to keep gambling in check.
      </p>

      <h2>The blurring line: gambling-like financial products</h2>
      <p>
        Here is where the picture gets fuzzier. Some newer money
        activities are not officially "gambling," but they can share
        features with it. This section is <strong>not financial
        advice</strong>. It does not tell you to buy, sell, trade, or
        avoid anything. It just describes why the line can feel
        blurry.
      </p>
      <p>
        What features do these activities sometimes share with
        gambling? Often a few of these:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          They are <strong>fast and app-based</strong>, with prices
          moving moment to moment.
        </li>
        <li>
          They involve <strong>chance or speculation</strong> —
          outcomes can be hard to predict.
        </li>
        <li>
          They can invite <strong>chasing losses</strong> — putting in
          more money to try to win back what was lost.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>A few examples people ask about:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Cryptocurrency trading.</strong> Buying and selling
          crypto can be very fast, runs around the clock, and prices
          can swing sharply. Some researchers have studied
          "gambling-like" patterns in frequent crypto trading (Mills
          &amp; Nower, 2023; Delfabbro et al., 2021).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>NFTs (non-fungible tokens).</strong> These are
          digital items bought and sold online, often hoping the price
          goes up. Some studies have noted gambling-like design
          features and have found overlap between gambling problems
          and buying digital assets like NFTs (Sklar et al.,
          <em>International Gambling Studies</em>, 2023).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Options and event (prediction) markets.</strong>
          Options are financial contracts whose value depends on what
          a stock or other asset does. In recent years, very-short-dated
          options — including so-called "zero-day" options that expire
          the same day — and easy-to-use trading apps have grown. So
          have <strong>event</strong> or <strong>prediction
          markets</strong>, where people put money on whether a
          specific future event will happen. Some public-health
          researchers have written about gambling-like features in
          these markets (Johnson, <em>Addiction</em>, 2026;
          <em>Science</em>, 2026).
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        It is worth saying clearly: many people use these products
        without harm, and reasonable people disagree about how to
        classify them. The point here is not to label any of them. It
        is simply that the <strong>line between investing and gambling
        can blur</strong>, especially when an activity is fast,
        app-based, and built around speculation. Some public-health
        voices have raised concerns about these gambling-like features.
        We report that as context, not as a verdict.
      </p>

      <h2>Why this matters now</h2>
      <p>Put the pieces together and the "why now" comes into focus:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>A 2018 court decision opened the door to legal sports
          betting, state by state.</li>
        <li>Gambling moved online, so it lives on the same phone you
          use for everything else.</li>
        <li>And some everyday financial apps now offer activities that
          can feel a lot like gambling.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The result is simple to state: there are <strong>more ways to
        gamble, in more places, more easily</strong> than there were a
        decade ago.
      </p>
      <p>
        That is not a reason to be afraid. It is a reason to understand.
        Most people who gamble do not develop problems. But more access
        can make gambling harm easier to slip into and harder to notice
        — which is exactly why learning the basics matters now. For
        warning signs and a short self-check, see <a
        href="/understand-gambling/warning-signs-risk-factors">Warning
        signs &amp; risk factors</a>.
      </p>

